{# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
   /heatmap — standalone full-tapestry interactive (v2)

   Iteration on v1 (initial carve-out). JM feedback after the first ship:
   the page had a horizontal scrollbar on the heatmap (only a slice of
   the tapestry was visible at a time), and clicking a cell navigated
   *away* to /bitcoin-vs-the-stock-market — taking the user out of the
   page they'd just landed on.

   v2 fixes both. Three structural changes:

   1) Full-canvas heatmap. The sidebar (THE PATTERN stat block) moves
      from a 280px right-rail to a horizontal stat strip BELOW the
      heatmap. The grid columns switch from a fixed 7px width to
      minmax(0, 1fr) fill on desktop, so all ~197 monthly columns
      fit edge-to-edge with no scrollbar. Mobile keeps the fixed-width
      column + horizontal scroll (no other way to show 197 cells on
      a phone). The wrapper max-width also expanded from 1180px to
      1400px to give the heatmap a more expansive canvas.

   2) §2 calc inline. The full BvSM §2 calculator markup is rendered
      directly below the heatmap. Same DOM IDs, same JS bindings;
      bvsm.js's existing init() picks it up identically to BvSM page.
      jumpToCalc() now finds its slider locally (no longer needs the
      cross-page navigation branch — though that branch stays in
      bvsm.js as a defensive fallback). Clicking a heatmap cell now
      scrolls down to the calc with the scenario pre-loaded, and the
      chart renders the wealth path for that window. No navigation
      away from /heatmap.

   3) CTA moves down. Now appears at the bottom, after the user has
      had a chance to engage with both the macro view (heatmap) and
      the micro view (single-scenario chart). It's the third act of
      the page: "see the full editorial argument that contextualizes
      what you've just explored."

   Result: a single immersive page. Macro → micro → narrative.
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ #}

<main class="heatmap-standalone">

    <section class="heatmap-hero">
        <h1>The <em>Bitcoin</em> Heatmap</h1>
        <p class="subtitle">
            Every monthly entry since 2010, every common holding horizon &mdash; bitcoin's outperformance against the S&amp;P 500 and the NASDAQ-100 across roughly 1,500 possible windows, in one grid.
        </p>
        <p class="heatmap-howto">
            Amber means bitcoin won; red means it lost; intensity shows by how much. <strong>Click any cell to load that exact entry into the calculator below.</strong>
        </p>
    </section>

